TY  - JOUR
T1  - Affective statistics: Influence of visual designs on the interpretation of public health data
AN  - 3283678138; 2027-04692-001
AB  - Effective visualisation is crucial for interpreting and disseminating data in both professional and public domains. This study investigates the impact of colour hue and visualisation modes – static maps, short videos, and augmented reality (AR) animations – on knowledge accuracy (KA), cognitive evaluation, and emotional response using January 2022 COVID-19 data from the continental U.S. Participants (N = 105) viewed maps depicting COVID-19 cases or vaccination rates in each mode and in either red or green hues. Results indicate that negative emotional impact was greater for static compared to video mode, but only in the green condition, while KA improved for static mode in both colour conditions and for AR in the red condition. Cognitive evaluations were not significantly affected by mode or colour. A second model with KA as outcome and including surprise and cognitive evaluation as mediators showed that static mode associated with improved KA, with surprise positively associated with KA scores, but only in video mode. The results suggest insights into effective health data visualisation strategies and the potential of AR technology for enhancing knowledge retention and engagement. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2025 APA, all rights reserved)
