TY  - JOUR
T1  - Educational gamification: motivation and engagement strategies
AN  - 3191227705
AB  - Gamified learning creates authentic situations for students to solve tasks, provides students with active learning opportunities, and is an effective way to cultivate problem-solving ability, critical thinking, creativity, etc. In this paper, we conduct an in-depth study of gamified learning and learning behavior modeling technology, choose the Hidden Markov Model as the technical support of the study, adopt the Bayesian Information Criterion to select the optimal number of hidden states of the model, and combine the K-means algorithm with the model optimization in model parameter estimation, which to a certain extent improves the speed of convergence in the process of learning behavior modeling. The game elements and learning activity elements have been integrated and migrated, and proposed gamified learning activity elements. Activity theory and self-determination theory were used to design a gamified learning activity process for the educational field. The game-based learning activity process was continuously revised and optimized by iterating the process with actual teaching cases. Subsequently, we merged qualitative and quantitative research to examine students’ gamified learning and the changes in their learning effects. The results showed that gamified learning produced significant facilitation (p<0.001) in all four dimensions of mind-flow experience, intrinsic motivation, knowledge retention, and transfer performance, with effect values of 1.05, 1.65, 1.00, and 1.08, respectively. This indicates that the gamified learning model can enable students to stimulate and maintain good motivation for learning, and further demonstrates that the process of designing gamified learning activities has effectiveness.
